"12 ounce bottle into tulip glass, bottled on 10/22/2014. Pours hazy deep reddish brown color with a 2 finger dense khaki head with good retention, that reduces to a small cap that lingers. Nice spotty soapy lacing clings around the glass. Aromas of caramel, brown sugar, toast, toffee, plum, fig, pear, apple, herbal, grass, and yeast earthiness. Nice and pleasant aromas with good balance of dark/bready malt, earthy hop, and fruity yeast notes; with decent strength. Taste of caramel, toast, toffee, brown sugar, brown bread, cocoa, plum, fig, apple, herbal, grass, light pine, light nuttiness, and yeast/toasted earthiness. Light earthy herbal bitterness on the finish; with lingering notes of caramel, toast, toffee, brown sugar, brown bread, cocoa, plum, fig, apple, light nuttiness, and herbal/toasted earthiness on the finish for a good bit. Very nice robustness and complexity and dark/bready malt, earthy hop, and light-moderate fruity yeast flavors; with a great malt/bitterness balance and zero cloying flavors after the finish. Medium carbonation and body; with a very smooth, fairly creamy/bready, and slightly sticky mouthfeel that is nice. Alcohol is very well hidden with minimal warming present after the finish. Overall this is a very good brown ale. All around nice complexity, robustness, and balance of dark/bready malt, earthy hop, and light-moderate fruity yeast flavors; and very smooth to drink for the ABV. A nicely enjoyable offering."
""
""
"Bottled on 10/14/2014: Pours chestnut brown color and almost looks like watery caramel with a huge looking foamy 2 finger tan head that faded slowly and left good spotty lacing going down the sides. Smells of caramel, toasted grains, brown sugar, wet wheat bread, metallic yeast funk, light piney hops, dry crackers and what I perceive as allspice; the spicy notes at the end give it the “festive” holiday aroma. No nuts in the nose, but all the malt of a brown ale. Taste is very similar but it has more hops which seem floral to go along with the pine cone taste, and it has additional spices like cumin and cinnamon which make the flavor way more winter seasonal. The toasted grains and malts are strong and work well with the hops and spices, but I’m not a huge winter warmer type so I was hoping for more brown ale basics but should have expected the spice rack in the mix. Mouthfeel is light and almost watery, with a lighter body, and a sweet malty finish that leaves a mix of spices like potpourri. Decent holiday beer, more winter warmer than brown ale IMO, but still decent overall yet not my cup of tea or favorite style (winter warmer aspect)."
